  8  /-!
  9  # Ordering on topologies and (co)induced topologies
 10  
 11  Topologies on a fixed type `α` are ordered, by reverse inclusion.
 12  That is, for topologies `t₁` and `t₂` on `α`, we write `t₁ ≤ t₂`
 13  if every set open in `t₂` is also open in `t₁`.
 14  (One also calls `t₁` finer than `t₂`, and `t₂` coarser than `t₁`.)
 15  
 16  Any function `f : α → β` induces
 17         `induced f : topological_space β → topological_space α`
 18  and  `coinduced f : topological_space α → topological_space β`.
 19  Continuity, the ordering on topologies and (co)induced topologies are
 20  related as follows:
 21  * The identity map (α, t₁) → (α, t₂) is continuous iff t₁ ≤ t₂.
 22  * A map f : (α, t) → (β, u) is continuous
 23      iff             t ≤ induced f u   (`continuous_iff_le_induced`)
 24      iff coinduced f t ≤ u             (`continuous_iff_coinduced_le`).
 25  
 26  Topologies on α form a complete lattice, with ⊥ the discrete topology
 27  and ⊤ the indiscrete topology.
 28  
 29  For a function f : α → β, (coinduced f, induced f) is a Galois connection
 30  between topologies on α and topologies on β.
 31  
 32  ## Implementation notes
 33  
 34  There is a Galois insertion between topologies on α (with the inclusion ordering)
 35  and all collections of sets in α. The complete lattice structure on topologies
 36  on α is defined as the reverse of the one obtained via this Galois insertion.
 37
